{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613987"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:40:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:40:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16336"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16336"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9027"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116454"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9027"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16336"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98453"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7515"},{"type":"tags","id":"7521"},{"type":"tags","id":"8399"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21474"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21478"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116454"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lens of the eye has a unique cellular organisation that is essential for its transparency and refractive properties.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the epithelial cell arrangement on the anterior surface of the lens?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Simple squamous cells, becoming columnar near equator","Simple cuboidal cells, becoming columnar near equator","Simple squamous cells, becoming cuboidal near equator","Simple columnar cells, becoming squamous near equator","Simple cuboidal cells, becoming squamous near equator"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lens has a single layer of \u003Cstrong\u003Esimple cuboidal epithelial cells on its anterior surface that become columnar near the equator\u003C/strong\u003E. At the equator, these cells elongate and differentiate into lens fibres that make up the bulk of the lens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other arrangements described are incorrect. \u003Cstrong\u003ESimple squamous cells becoming columnar\u003C/strong\u003E is inaccurate because the epithelium starts as cuboidal, not squamous. \u003Cstrong\u003ESimple squamous cells becoming cuboidal\u003C/strong\u003E would not support proper lens fibre formation. \u003Cstrong\u003ESimple columnar cells becoming squamous\u003C/strong\u003E reverses the actual process, as the cells become more elongated (columnar) at the equator, not less. \u003Cstrong\u003ESimple cuboidal cells becoming squamous\u003C/strong\u003E also contradicts the normal development, where cells elongate rather than flatten at the equator.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis specific arrangement of epithelial cells is crucial for the continuous production of new lens fibres throughout life, maintaining lens growth and transparency.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The lens epithelium consists of simple cuboidal cells that become columnar near the equator where they differentiate into lens fibres.","The posterior surface of the lens lacks epithelial cells as these cells differentiate into lens fibres during development."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98453"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16336"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98453"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T10:14:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T10:16:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9027"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116454"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4941"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":[],"descripti